.
"Gsus4 always leads to the One(G Major) by raising the third. Just like Jesus is leading us to the One and was raised on the third.
.
Gsus4 is not dominant, its suspended. Just like Jesus was. He was suspended and came to serve, not to be served.
.
Gsus4 has its own spiritual but also powerful meaning behind it. You guys have picked an awesome name for your shop."

@ecodetrave got me thinking about the opening 'mystery chord" from The Beatles song Hard Days Night. This recording is based on the page from The Beatles Complete Scores book about one post back. Since I only have two hands instead of six, I used my trusty @tcelectronic #ditto pedal to layer these sounds. The click is me counting in so I could play each part at the right time. The Ditto will let you layer as many sounds as you want. If you notice on the score, guitar 2 is a twelve string. I don't have one, so I played the chord once as written then an octave higher to emulate the 12. There's also a low D in the bass which I used a drop D tuning for. I think I got fairly close, but I'm sure the Beatles had a little going on than just this. Anyway, just a fun experiment. If you are not familiar with this song...you should be!!  Also if you compare this pitch with the Beatles original recording you'll hear they are different. I'm pretty sure the speed on the original was sped up making a slightly sharper pitch. TOP: Last week I'm teaching Riley (sweet, funny 13 y/o) a new way to play a G chord so she can add in the sus4 with her 1st finger for "Dead Flowers", a Stones she wanted to learn. She's really struggling with it and getting frustrated. I'm checking her finger placement and notice her "finger placement". "Uh, Riley. You tryin' to tell me somethin'?" She laughs and  swears it's accidental! Okay, I believe her.

BOTTOM: She comes is yesterday. "How you doing with the changes for "Dead Flowers", I ask. "I still can't get that G sup chord", she says. "Gsus4, and what did I tell you about using that word here. Hard, challenging, but none of that 'can't' crap!" She corrects herself, "it's really hard." Alright, let me see how ur doin' with it. (typical teen whining and griping follows). I look down and see the same "finger placement." Only now the nail is painted red. And it's the ONLY nail on that hand with polish! 
I confess that fingering that chord can make your "finger" do that, but you tell me -- accidental, or not?
